text:
Madison Ave., east side, north from and including East 52nd Street. The 2-story building on the N.E. corner of East 52nd Street, is the Walker-Gordon Laboratory with the Juilliard Music Foundation Building adjoining it on the east.

April 9, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

57-89 East 52nd Street, north side, from east of Madison to Park Aves. The large building in the background is the Racquet and Tennis Club.

August 15, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

Madison Avenue, S.W. corner of 53rd Street, from clearing at N.E. corner of 52nd Street. This clearing was left by demolition of the Walker-Gordon Laboratory, and will be occupied by a new 30-story building.

August 15, 1929.

P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

(1) Madison Avenue, west side, north from 53rd to 56th Streets, seen from the N.E. corner of 52nd Street. In the center background the new Hotel Savoy-Plaza at the S.E. corner of Fifth Avenue almost completely hides the new Sherry Netherland on the N.E. corner. August 15, 1929.

P.L. Sperr, Photographer.

(2) The same, as seen from building at the S.E. corner of East 52nd Street, showing a more inclusive view farther north. The prominent buildings shown are in the mid-town Fifth Ave. zone. March 4, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

General View Midtown Manhattan, in the East 40's: Looking southeastward from 52nd Street and Madison Avenue showing the skyscrapers in the Grand Central area. From left to right are the News, Chrysler, Chanin (flag atop) and New York Central Railroad Buildings.

View 3 is southwestward from 52nd Street near the East River toward the Chrysler building.

P. L. Sperr

Views 1,2: March 4, 1930
View 3: June 23, 1930
